<h2>From flag to fix: a real walkthrough</h2>

<p>Take the first flag — <code>projects</code> has an
<code>org_id</code> column but RLS is disabled. The agent's job:
read the policy, write the migration, verify.</p>

<h3>Step 1: get the existing schema</h3>

<pre><code>db_table_schema(&lcub; schema: "public", table: "projects" &rcub;)

→ columns: [id uuid, org_id uuid, name text, created_at timestamptz],
  rls: &lcub; enabled: false, policies: [] &rcub;,
  indexes: [...]</code></pre>

<p>Confirms the audit. Now the agent knows the column shape and can
write the migration without guessing.</p>

<h3>Step 2: find every read site</h3>

<pre><code>schema_usage(&lcub; schema: "public", object: "projects" &rcub;)

→ reads:  ["app/api/projects/route.ts:8 — .from('projects').select('*')",
           "app/dashboard/page.tsx:42 — .from('projects').select('id, name')"],
  writes: ["app/api/projects/route.ts:31 — .from('projects').insert(...)"],
  rpc_refs: []</code></pre>

<p>Two reads, one write. The agent can now reason about which need a
manual filter and which will be covered by RLS.</p>

<h3>Step 3: write the migration</h3>

<pre><code>alter table public.projects enable row level security;

create policy "projects: org members can read"
  on public.projects
  for select
  using (
    exists (
      select 1 from public.org_membership m
      where m.user_id = auth.uid()
        and m.org_id = projects.org_id
    )
  );

create policy "projects: org admins can write"
  on public.projects
  for all
  using (
    exists (
      select 1 from public.org_membership m
      where m.user_id = auth.uid()
        and m.org_id = projects.org_id
        and m.role = 'admin'
    )
  );</code></pre>

<p>The agent writes this migration with full knowledge of the schema
shape (the <code>org_membership</code> join), not from a guess. The
policies map cleanly to existing app-code expectations.</p>

<h3>Step 4: refresh and re-audit</h3>

<pre><code>db_reef_refresh()
tenant_leak_audit(&lcub;&rcub;)

→ &lcub; flagged: [...3 remaining...], passed: 24, total_tenant_tables: 27 &rcub;</code></pre>

<p>The <code>projects</code> table is gone from the flagged list. The
remaining three are still there for the next round.</p>

<h2>The findings persist</h2>

<p>Important detail: the audit results live in Reef — agentmako's
durable findings store. That means:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The next agent session knows what's already been audited.</li>
  <li>If you ack a finding ("policy_wrong_column on
  <code>manager_district</code> — intentional, this is a global
  reference table not tenant-keyed"), the ack is bound to the
  finding's identity, not its line number. Future re-runs respect
  it.</li>
  <li>If a migration changes the schema such that a previously-acked
  finding no longer matches the same target, the ack auto-revokes —
  forcing a re-review instead of silently hiding a new bug.</li>
</ul>

<p>This matters because tenant-leak audits aren't one-shot. Schemas
change. Migrations land. Someone disables RLS for a hotfix and forgets
to turn it back on. Persistent findings make this catch the regression
on the next run, not three months later.</p>

<h2>Beyond Supabase</h2>

<p>The same audit shape works for any Postgres app — Drizzle, Prisma,
Kysely, raw <code>pg</code>. The tools that change:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Supabase apps: <code>auth.uid()</code> is the session anchor;
  policies usually reference an <code>org_membership</code> or
  <code>workspace_membership</code> join.</li>
  <li>Generic Postgres: session anchor is whatever your auth layer
  sets via <code>SET app.user_id = '...'</code>; policies reference
  that.</li>
  <li>Drizzle / Prisma / Kysely: the <code>.from()</code> style call
  detection becomes ORM-method detection. agentmako's
  <code>schema_usage</code> covers all of these.</li>
</ul>

<p>The pattern doesn't depend on Supabase specifically. It depends on:
(a) RLS as the enforcement layer, (b) a structured way to query schema
+ policies, (c) a structured way to find app-code call sites. Any
stack with those three has the same audit available.</p>

<h2>What this means for shipping</h2>

<p>Add the audit to your pre-commit hook, or run it weekly, or both.
Either way:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Your AI coding agent's mistakes become catchable. The agent ships
  a route without a tenant filter; the audit flags it; the agent
  re-runs the policy check before merging.</li>
  <li>Schema migrations don't silently regress security. RLS-disabled
  tables surface immediately, not at the next external audit.</li>
  <li>Service-role-key-on-client mistakes get caught by the auxiliary
  checks in the same audit pass.</li>
</ul>

<p>None of this requires you to write a custom static analyzer. The
audit is a single MCP tool call. The trick is having a context engine
that can see the database <em>and</em> the code <em>and</em> the
import graph in one place — which is exactly what
<a href="/">agentmako</a> ships.</p>

<h2>Try it</h2>

<p>If you're on Supabase or Postgres and have RLS-protected tables:</p>

<ol>
  <li><code>npm install -g agentmako</code></li>
  <li><code>agentmako connect .</code> — interactive, prompts for your DB URL (stored in your OS keychain).</li>
  <li>In your agent, call <code>tenant_leak_audit</code> with no args.</li>
  <li>Read the flagged list. Fix the easy ones. Ack the intentional
  ones with a reason.</li>
</ol>

<p>It takes about 30 seconds. The first time you run it, you'll
probably find at least one issue you didn't know was there. That's
the point — these bugs are invisible until something explicitly looks
for them.</p>

<p>Better to find your tenant leak from a tool than from a screenshot
in a support ticket.</p>

